# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: aleut
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:aleut/aleut] In the Aleut language, they are known by the endonyms **Unangan** (eastern dialect) and **Unangas** (western dialect); both terms mean "people".
[src:aleut/aleut] The Russian term "Aleut" was a general term used for both the Native population of the Aleutian Islands and their neighbors to the east in the Kodiak Archipelago, who were also referred to as "Pacific Eskimos" or Sugpiat/Alutiit.
[src:aleut/aleut] Aleut people traditionally speak Unangam Tunuu, the Aleut language, although nowadays most speak English and Russian in their respective countries as a result of colonization.
[src:aleut/aleut] An estimated 150 people in the United States and five people in Russia speak Aleut, although there are ongoing revitalization efforts.
[src:aleut/aleut] The language belongs to the Eskaleut language family and includes three dialects: Eastern Aleut, spoken on the Eastern Aleutian, Shumagin, Fox and Pribilof Islands; Atkan, spoken on Atka and Bering islands; and the now extinct Attuan dialect.
[src:aleut/aleut] The Pribilof Islands has the highest number of active speakers of Unangam Tunuu.
[src:aleut/aleut] Most Native elders speak Aleut, but it is rare for common people to speak the language fluently.
[src:aleut/aleut] Beginning in 1829, Aleut was written in the Cyrillic script.
[src:aleut/aleut] From 1870, the language has been written in the Latin script.
[src:aleut/aleut] An Aleut dictionary and grammar have been published, and portions of the Bible were translated into Aleut.
[src:aleut/aleut] Aleuts historically lived throughout the Aleutian Islands, the Shumagin Islands, and the far western part of the Alaska Peninsula, with an estimated population of around 25,000 prior to European contact.
[src:aleut/aleut] In the 1820s, the Russian-American Company administered a large portion of the North Pacific during a Russian-led expansion of the fur trade.
[src:aleut/aleut] They resettled many Aleut families to the Commander Islands (within the Aleutsky District of the Kamchatka Krai in Russia) and to the Pribilof Islands (in Alaska).
[src:aleut/aleut] These continue to have majority-Aleut communities.
[src:aleut/aleut] According to the 2000 census, 11,941 people identified as being Aleut, while 17,000 identified as having partial Aleut ancestry.
[src:aleut/aleut] Prior to sustained European contact, approximately 25,000 Aleut lived in the archipelago.
[src:aleut/aleut] The Encyclopædia Britannica Online states that more than 15,000 people have Aleut ancestry in the early 21st century.
[src:aleut/aleut] Aleuts suffered high fatalities in the 19th and early 20th centuries from Eurasian infectious diseases to which they had no immunity.
[src:aleut/aleut] In addition, the population suffered as their customary lifestyles were disrupted.
[src:aleut/aleut] Russian traders, and later Europeans, married Aleut women and had families with them.
[src:aleut/aleut] Russian Orthodox missionaries arrived in Kodiak in 1794.
[src:aleut/aleut] Of the numerous Russian Orthodox congregations in Alaska, most are majority Alaska Native or Native Alaskan in ethnicity.
[src:aleut/aleut] One of the earliest Christian martyrs in North America was Saint Peter the Aleut.
[src:aleut/aleut] Russian traders "took Aleut women and children hostage" to force Aleut men to hunt foxes and sea otters so the Russians could have their pelts, and often additionally enslaved Aleut men.
[src:aleut/aleut] In the 18th century, Russian *promyshlenniki* traders established settlements on the islands.
[src:aleut/aleut] There was high demand for the furs that the Aleuts provided from hunting.
[src:aleut/aleut] In 1783, Japanese sailor Daikokuya Kōdayū came into contact with these Russians and the native Aleuts, after getting shipwrecked on Amchitka Island with his crew.
[src:aleut/aleut] This occurred during Japan's Sakoku period of 1635 and 1854, when Japanese citizens were banned from leaving their homeland.
[src:aleut/aleut] Kōdayū lived among Russians until 1792, and when he returned home to Japan, he bought with him a Russian map which depicted the true shape of Australia, with prior Japanese maps depicting Australia as double its size and with New Guinea still attached.
[src:aleut/aleut] Kōdayū's encounter with the Aleuts was depicted in the 1992 Japanese film *Dreams of Russia*, which was based on his story.
[src:aleut/aleut] While Kōdayū was living on Amchitka in May 1784, the local Aleuts there revolted against the Russian traders.
[src:aleut/aleut] (The Russians had a small trading post there.) According to the Aleuts, in an account recorded by the Japanese castaways and published in 2004, otters were decreasing year by year.
[src:aleut/aleut] The Russians paid the Aleuts less and less in goods in return for the furs they made.
[src:aleut/aleut] The Japanese learned that the Aleuts felt the situation was at crisis.
[src:aleut/aleut] The leading Aleuts negotiated with the Russians, saying they had failed to deliver enough supplies in return for furs.
[src:aleut/aleut] After the four leaders had been killed, the Aleuts began to move from Amchitka to neighboring islands.
[src:aleut/aleut] Nezimov, leader of the Russian group, was jailed after the whole incident was reported to Russian officials.
[src:aleut/aleut] In 1814, to obtain more of the commercially valuable otter pelts, a Russian company brought a party of conscripted Aleut hunters to the coastal island of San Nicolas, near the Alta California-Baja California border.
[src:aleut/aleut] The locally resident Nicoleño nation sought a payment from the Aleut hunters for the large number of otters being killed in the area.
[src:aleut/aleut] Disagreement arose, turning violent; an Aleut was killed, and in retaliation Aleuts killed a number of Nicoleño (the exact amount is unknown).
[src:aleut/aleut] In 1835, the remaining Nicoleños were removed from the island, except for one woman and possibly her child, who were left behind.
[src:aleut/aleut] In 1853 that woman, later christened Juana Maria, was found and taken to Santa Barbara.
[src:aleut/aleut] She may have been the last living Nicoleñan, as what happened to the others after they were brought to the mainland is unknown (Juana Maria, *the Lone Woman of San Nicolas*).
[src:aleut/aleut] When World War II broke out, the Aleutian Islands were under the control of the United States as they had been since March 1867, when they were included in the U.S. purchase of Alaska from Russia.
[src:aleut/aleut] In June 1942, Japanese forces occupied Kiska and Attu Islands in the western Aleutians, with this representing their northernmost region of operation in the Pacific War, which covered an area extending as far south as Australia.
[src:aleut/aleut] They later transported 41 captive Attu Islanders to Otaru, Hokkaido, where they were held as prisoners of war in harsh conditions.
[src:aleut/aleut] Roughly half of them died while they were imprisoned.
[src:aleut/aleut] The deaths were caused by the spread of tuberculosis among the imprisoned Aleuts, and starvation/malnutrition, as the Japanese primarily fed them small portions of rice.
[src:aleut/aleut] Aleut chief Mike Hodikoff and his son George died after eating poisoned food from a garbage bin, since they were starving in the prison.
[src:aleut/aleut] The Japanese also forced the imprisoned Aleut children to learn the Japanese language, threatening to kill them if they did not.
[src:aleut/aleut] Alex Prossoff, a survivor of the prison camp, later said in 1988, "as long as Americans are fight for my country I'll be on their side.
[src:aleut/aleut] I told them Japs destroy our homes, make us prisoners and put us on a land where we cannot talk his language.
[src:aleut/aleut] The World War II campaign by the United States to retake Attu and Kiska was a significant component of the operations in the American and Pacific theaters.
[src:aleut/aleut] In total, about 75 died in American internment and 22 died while prisoners of the Japanese.
[src:aleut/aleut] The Aleut Restitution Act of 1988 was an attempt by Congress to compensate the survivors.
[src:aleut/aleut] On June 17, 2017, the U.S. government formally apologized for the internment of the Unangan people and their treatment in the camps.
[src:aleut/aleut] Before their way of life was changed by major influences from the outside world, approximately 25,000 Aleuts were located on the archipelago.
[src:aleut/aleut] Foreign diseases, harsh treatment and disruption of aboriginal society soon reduced the population to less than one-tenth this number.
[src:aleut/aleut] According to the 1885 book *The Island World of the Pacific Ocean*, the Aleutian Islands had a population of roughly 3,000 during that time.
[src:aleut/aleut] The 1910 Census count showed 1,491 Aleuts.
[src:aleut/aleut] In the 2000 Census, 11,941 people identified as being Aleut; nearly 17,000 said Aleuts were among their ancestors.
[src:aleut/aleut] This rose to 13,805 people in the 2020 Census.
[src:aleut/aleut] Aleuts historically constructed partially underground houses called *barabara*.
[src:aleut/aleut] According to Lillie McGarvey, a 20th-century Aleut leader, *barabara**s* keep "occupants dry from the frequent rains, warm at all times, and snugly sheltered from the high winds common to the area".
[src:aleut/aleut] Aleuts traditionally built houses by digging an oblong square pit in the ground, usually 50 by 20 feet (15.2 by 6.1 m) or smaller.
[src:aleut/aleut] The pit was then covered by a roof framed with driftwood, thatched with grass, and then covered with earth for insulation.
[src:aleut/aleut] Inside trenches were dug along the sides, with mats placed on top to keep them clean.
[src:aleut/aleut] The bedrooms were at the back of the lodge, opposite the entrance.
[src:aleut/aleut] Several families would stay in one house, with their own designated areas.
[src:aleut/aleut] Rather than fireplaces or bonfires in the middle, lanterns were hung in the house.
[src:aleut/aleut] Traditional Aleuts survive by hunting and gathering.
[src:aleut/aleut] They fish for salmon, crabs, shellfish, and cod, as well as hunt sea mammals such as seal, walrus, and whales.
[src:aleut/aleut] They can process fish and sea mammals in a variety of ways: dried, smoked, or roasted.
[src:aleut/aleut] Caribou, muskoxen, deer, moose, whale, and other types of game were eaten roasted or preserved for later use.
[src:aleut/aleut] They dried berries; often processed as *alutiqqutigaq*, a mixture of berries, fat, and fish.
[src:aleut/aleut] The boiled skin and blubber of a whale is a delicacy, as is that of walrus.
[src:aleut/aleut] Today, many Aleut continue to eat customary and locally sourced foods but also buy processed foods from abroad, which is expensive in Alaska.
[src:aleut/aleut] A full list of their ethnobotany has been compiled, with 65 documented plant uses.
[src:aleut/aleut] Customary arts of the Aleuts include weapon-making, building of *baidarkas* (special hunting boats), weaving, figurines, clothing, carving, and mask making.
[src:aleut/aleut] Men as well as women often carved ivory and wood.
[src:aleut/aleut] Nineteenth century craftsmen were famed for their ornate wooden hunting hats, which feature elaborate and colorful designs and may be trimmed with sea lion whiskers, feathers, and walrus ivory.
[src:aleut/aleut] Andrew Gronholdt of the Shumagin Islands has played a vital role in reviving the ancient art of building the *chagudax* or bentwood hunting visors.
[src:aleut/aleut] Aleut women sewed finely stitched, waterproof parkas from seal gut and wove fine baskets from sea-lyme grass (*Elymus mollis*).
[src:aleut/aleut] Some Aleut women continue to weave ryegrass baskets.
[src:aleut/aleut] Aleut arts are practiced and taught throughout the state of Alaska.
[src:aleut/aleut] As many Aleut have moved out of the islands to other parts of the state, they have taken with them the knowledge of their arts.
[src:aleut/aleut] They have also adopted new materials and methods for their art, including serigraphy, video art, and installation art.
[src:aleut/aleut] Aleut carving, distinct in each region, has attracted traders for centuries, including early Europeans and other Alaska Natives.
[src:aleut/aleut] Historically, carving was a male art and leadership attribute whereas today it is done by both genders.
[src:aleut/aleut] Most commonly the carvings of walrus ivory and driftwood originated as part of making hunting weapons.
[src:aleut/aleut] Sculptural carvings depict local animals, such as seals and whales.
[src:aleut/aleut] Aleut sculptors also have carved human figures.
[src:aleut/aleut] Aleuts also carve walrus ivory for other uses, such as jewelry and sewing needles.
[src:aleut/aleut] Jewelry is made with designs specific to the region of each people.
[src:aleut/aleut] Each clan would have a specific style to signify their origin.
[src:aleut/aleut] Jewelry ornaments were made for piercing lips (labrum), nose, and ears, as well as for necklaces.
[src:aleut/aleut] Each woman had her own sewing needles, which she made, and that often had detailed end of animal heads.
[src:aleut/aleut] The main Aleut method of basketry was false embroidery (overlay).
[src:aleut/aleut] Strands of grasses or reeds were overlaid upon the basic weaving surface, to obtain a plastic effect.
[src:aleut/aleut] Early Aleut women created baskets and woven mats of exceptional technical quality, using only their thumbnail, grown long and then sharpened, as a tool.
[src:aleut/aleut] Today, Aleut weavers continue to produce woven grass pieces of a remarkable cloth-like texture, works of modern art with roots in ancient tradition.
[src:aleut/aleut] Birch bark, puffin feathers, and baleen are also commonly used by the Aleuts in basketry.
[src:aleut/aleut] The Aleut term for grass basket is *qiigam aygaaxsii*.
[src:aleut/aleut] One Aleut leader recognized by the State of Alaska for her work in teaching and reviving Aleut basketry was Anfesia Shapsnikoff.
[src:aleut/aleut] Her life and accomplishments are portrayed in the book *Moments Rightly Placed* (1998).
[src:aleut/aleut] Masks were created to portray figures of their myths and oral history.
[src:aleut/aleut] The Atka people believed that another people lived in their land before them.
[src:aleut/aleut] They portrayed such ancients in their masks, which show anthropomorphic creatures named in their language.
[src:aleut/aleut] Knut Bergsland says their word means "like those found in caves." Masks were generally carved from wood and were decorated with paints made from berries or other natural products.
[src:aleut/aleut] Feathers were inserted into holes carved out for extra decoration.
[src:aleut/aleut] These masks were used in ceremonies ranging from dances to praises, each with its own meaning and purpose.
[src:aleut/aleut] The tattoos and piercings of the Aleuts demonstrated accomplishments as well as their religious views.
[src:aleut/aleut] They believed their body art would please the spirits of the animals and make any evil go away.
[src:aleut/aleut] The body orifices were believed to be pathways for the entry of evil entities.
[src:aleut/aleut] By piercing their orifices: the nose, the mouth, and ears, they would stop evil entities, *khoughkh*, from entering their bodies.
[src:aleut/aleut] Body art also enhanced their beauty, social status, and spiritual authority.
[src:aleut/aleut] Before the 19th century, piercings and tattoos were very common among Aleuts, especially among women.
[src:aleut/aleut] Piercings, such as the nose pin, were common among both men and women and were usually performed a few days after birth.
[src:aleut/aleut] The ornament was made of various materials, a piece of bark or bone, or an eagle's feather shaft.
[src:aleut/aleut] From time to time, adult women decorated the nose pins by hanging pieces of amber and coral from strings on it; the semi-precious objects dangled down to their chins.
[src:aleut/aleut] The Aleuts pierced holes around the rim of their ears with dentalium shells (tooth shells or tusk shells), bone, feathers, dried bird wings or skulls and/or amber.
[src:aleut/aleut] Materials associated with birds were important, as birds were considered to defend animals in the spirit world.
[src:aleut/aleut] A man would wear sea lion whiskers in his ears as a trophy of his expertise as a hunter.
[src:aleut/aleut] Worn for decorative reasons, and sometimes to signify social standing, reputation, and the age of the wearer, Aleuts would pierce their lower lips with walrus ivory and wear beads or bones.
[src:aleut/aleut] The individual with the most piercings held the highest respect.
[src:aleut/aleut] Tattooing for women began when they reached physical maturity, after menstruation, at about age 20.
[src:aleut/aleut] Historically, men received their first tattoo after killing their first animal, an important rite of passage.
[src:aleut/aleut] Sometimes tattoos signaled social class.
[src:aleut/aleut] For example, the daughter of a wealthy, famous ancestor or father would work hard at her tattoos to show the accomplishments of that ancestor or father.
[src:aleut/aleut] They would sew, or prick, different designs on the chin, the side of the face, or under the nose.
[src:aleut/aleut] Aleuts developed in one of the harshest climates in the world, and learned to create and protect warmth.
[src:aleut/aleut] Both men and women wore parkas that extended below the knees.
[src:aleut/aleut] The women wore the skin of seal or sea-otter, and the men wore bird skin parkas, the feathers turned in or out depending on the weather.
[src:aleut/aleut] When the men were hunting on the water, they wore waterproof parkas made from seal or sea-lion guts, or the entrails of bear, walrus, or whales.
[src:aleut/aleut] Parkas had a hood that could be cinched, as could the wrist openings, so water could not get in.
[src:aleut/aleut] Men wore breeches made from the esophageal skin of seals.
[src:aleut/aleut] Children wore parkas made of downy eagle skin with tanned bird skin caps.
[src:aleut/aleut] They called these parkas *kameikas**,* meaning 'rain gear' in the English language.
[src:aleut/aleut] Sea-lions, harbor seals, and sea otters are the most abundant marine mammals.
[src:aleut/aleut] The men brought home the skins and prepared them by soaking them in urine and stretching them.
[src:aleut/aleut] Preparation of the gut for clothing involved several steps.
[src:aleut/aleut] The prepared intestines were turned inside out.
[src:aleut/aleut] A bone knife was used to remove the muscle tissue and fat from the walls of the intestine.
[src:aleut/aleut] The gut was cut and stretched, and fastened to stakes to dry.
[src:aleut/aleut] It was then cut and sewn to make waterproof parkas, bags, and other receptacles.
[src:aleut/aleut] On some hunting trips, the men would take several women with them.
[src:aleut/aleut] They would catch birds and prepare the carcasses and feathers for future use.
[src:aleut/aleut] They caught puffins (*Lunda cirrhata*, *Fratercula corniculata*), guillemots, and murres.
[src:aleut/aleut] It took 40 skins of tufted puffin and 60 skins of horned puffin to make one parka.
[src:aleut/aleut] A woman would need a year for all the labor to make one parka.
[src:aleut/aleut] All parkas were decorated with bird feathers, beard bristles of seal and sea-lion, beaks of sea parrots, bird claws, sea otter fur, dyed leather, and caribou hair sewn in the seams.
[src:aleut/aleut] Women made needles from the wing bones of seabirds.
[src:aleut/aleut] They made thread from the sinews of different animals and fish guts.
[src:aleut/aleut] A thin strip of seal intestine could also be used, twisted to form a thread.
[src:aleut/aleut] The women grew their thumbnail extra long and sharpened it.
[src:aleut/aleut] They could split threads to make them as fine as a hair.
[src:aleut/aleut] They used vermilion paint, hematite, the ink bag of the octopus, and the root of a kind of grass or vine to color the threads.
[src:aleut/aleut] The interior regions of the rough, mountainous Aleutian Islands provided little in terms of natural resources for the Aleutian people.
[src:aleut/aleut] They collected stones for weapons, tools, stoves or lamps.
[src:aleut/aleut] They collected and dried grasses for their woven baskets.
[src:aleut/aleut] For everything else, the Aleuts had learned to use the fish and mammals they caught and processed to satisfy their needs.
[src:aleut/aleut] To hunt sea mammals and to travel between islands, the Aleuts became experts of sailing and navigation.
[src:aleut/aleut] While hunting, they used small watercraft called *baidarkas.* For regular travel, they used their large *baidara**s*.
[src:aleut/aleut] The *baidara* was a large, open, walrus-skin-covered boat.
[src:aleut/aleut] Aleut families used it when traveling among the islands.
[src:aleut/aleut] It was also used to transport goods for trade, and warriors took them to battle.
[src:aleut/aleut] The *baidarka* (small skin boat) was a small boat covered in sea lion skin.
[src:aleut/aleut] It was developed and used for hunting because of its sturdiness and maneuverability.
[src:aleut/aleut] Aleut *baidarka* resembles that of a Yup'ik kayak, but it is hydrodynamically sleeker and faster.
[src:aleut/aleut] They made the *baidarka* for one or two persons only.
[src:aleut/aleut] The deck was made with a sturdy chamber, the sides of the craft were nearly vertical and the bottom was rounded.
[src:aleut/aleut] Most one-man *baidarka**s* were about 16 feet (4.9 m) long and 20 inches (51 cm) wide, whereas a two-man was on average about 20 feet (6.1 m) long and 24 inches (61 cm) wide.
[src:aleut/aleut] It was from the *baidarka* that Aleut men would stand on the water to hunt from the sea.
[src:aleut/aleut] The Aleuts hunted small sea mammals with barbed darts and harpoons slung from throwing boards.
[src:aleut/aleut] These boards gave precision as well as some extra distance to these weapons.
[src:aleut/aleut] Harpoons were also called throwing-arrows when the pointed head fit loosely into the socket of the foreshaft and the head was able to detach from the harpoon when it penetrated an animal, and remain in the wound.
[src:aleut/aleut] The simple Aleut harpoon consisted of four main parts: the wooden shaft, the bone foreshaft, and the bonehead (tip) with barbs pointed backward.
[src:aleut/aleut] The barbed head was loosely fitted into the socket of the foreshaft so that when the animal was stabbed, it pulled the head away from the rest of the harpoon.
[src:aleut/aleut] The sharp barbs penetrated with ease, but could not be pulled out.
[src:aleut/aleut] The bone tip is fastened to a length of braided twine meanwhile; the hunter held the other end of the twine in his hand.
[src:aleut/aleut] The compound harpoon was the most prevalent weapon of the Aleuts.
[src:aleut/aleut] Also known as the toggle-head spear, it was about the same size as the simple harpoon and used to hunt the same animals, however, this harpoon provided a more efficient and lethal weapon.
[src:aleut/aleut] The longest part was the shaft with the thicker stalk closer to the tip of the harpoon.
[src:aleut/aleut] The shaft was fitted into the socket of the fore shaft and a bone ring was then placed over the joint to hold the two pieces together, as well as, protecting the wooden shaft from splitting.
[src:aleut/aleut] Connected to the fore shaft of the harpoon is the toggle head spear tip.
[src:aleut/aleut] This tip was made of two sub shafts that break apart on impact with an animal.
[src:aleut/aleut] The upper sub shaft held the razor stone head and attached to the lower sub shaft with a small braided twine loop.
[src:aleut/aleut] Once the tip penetrates the animal the upper sub head broke off from the rest of the shaft, however, since it was still connected with the braided loop it rotated the head into a horizontal position inside the animal's body so that it could not get away from the hunter.
[src:aleut/aleut] The throwing lance may be distinguished from a harpoon because all its pieces are fixed and immovable.
[src:aleut/aleut] A lance was a weapon of war and it was also used to kill large marine animals after it has already been harpooned.
[src:aleut/aleut] The throwing lance usually consisted of three parts: a wooden shaft, a bone ring or belt, and the compound head that was made with a barbed bonehead and a stone tip.
[src:aleut/aleut] The length of the compound head was equivalent to the distance between the planes of a man's chest to his back.
[src:aleut/aleut] The lance would penetrate the chest and pass through the chest cavity and exit from the back.
[src:aleut/aleut] The bone ring was designed to break after impact so that the shaft could be used again for another kill.
[src:aleut/aleut] They buried their dead ancestors near the village.
[src:aleut/aleut] Archeologists have found many different types of burials, dating from a variety of periods, in the Aleutian Islands.
[src:aleut/aleut] Aleuts developed burial styles that were accommodated to local conditions, and honored the dead.
[src:aleut/aleut] They have had four main types of burials: *umqan*, cave, above-ground sarcophagi, and burials connected to communal houses.
[src:aleut/aleut] Cave burials have been found throughout the eastern Aleutian Islands.
[src:aleut/aleut] The human remains are buried in shallow graves at the rear of the cave.
[src:aleut/aleut] These caves tend to be next to middens and near villages.
[src:aleut/aleut] Some grave goods have been found in the caves associated with such burials.
[src:aleut/aleut] For example, a deconstructed boat was found in a burial cave on Kanaga Island.
[src:aleut/aleut] There were no other major finds of grave goods in the vicinity.
[src:aleut/aleut] Throughout the Aleutian Islands, gravesites have been found that are above-ground sarcophagi.
[src:aleut/aleut] These sarcophagi are left exposed, with no attempt to bury the dead in the ground.
[src:aleut/aleut] These burials tend to be isolated and limited to the remains of adult males, which may indicate a specific ritual practice.
[src:aleut/aleut] In the Near Islands, isolated graves have also been found with the remains, and not just the sarcophagus, left exposed on the surface.
[src:aleut/aleut] This way of erecting sarcophagi above ground is not as common as *umqan* and cave burials, but it is still widespread.
[src:aleut/aleut] Another type of practice has been to bury remains in areas next to the communal houses of the settlement.
[src:aleut/aleut] Human remains are abundant in such sites.
[src:aleut/aleut] They indicate a pattern of burying the dead within the main activity areas of the settlement.
[src:aleut/aleut] These burials consist of small pits adjacent to the houses and scattered around them.
[src:aleut/aleut] In these instances, mass graves are common for women and children.
[src:aleut/aleut] This type of mortuary practice has been mainly found in the Near Islands.
[src:aleut/aleut] In addition to these four main types, other kinds of burials have been found in the Aleutian Islands.
[src:aleut/aleut] These more isolated examples in include mummification, private burial houses, abandoned houses, etc.
[src:aleut/aleut] To date, such examples are not considered to be part of a larger, unifying cultural practice.
[src:aleut/aleut] The findings discussed represent only the sites that have been excavated.
[src:aleut/aleut] The variety of mortuary practices mostly did not include the ritual of including extensive grave goods, as has been found in other cultures.
[src:aleut/aleut] The remains so far have been mainly found with other human and faunal remains.
[src:aleut/aleut] The addition of objects to "accompany" the dead is rare.
[src:aleut/aleut] Archaeologists have been trying to dissect the absence of grave goods, but their findings have been ambiguous and do not really help the academic community to understand these practices more.
[src:aleut/aleut] Not much information is known about the ritual parts of burying the dead.
[src:aleut/aleut] Archeologists and anthropologists have not found much evidence related to burial rituals.
[src:aleut/aleut] This lack of ritual evidence could hint at either no ritualized ceremony, or one that has not yet been revealed in the archaeological record.
[src:aleut/aleut] As a result, archaeologists cannot decipher the context to understand exactly why a certain type of burial was used in particular cases.
[src:aleut/aleut] In *Snow Crash*, a science fiction novel by American writer Neal Stephenson, a central character named Raven is portrayed as an Aleut with incredible toughness and hunting skill.
[src:aleut/aleut] The story is about revenge due in part to perceived mistreatment of the Aleuts.
[src:aleut/aleut] In the book *Island of the Blue Dolphins* by American writer Scott O'Dell, Aleuts attack a tribe of Native Americans that live on a small island off the coast of California.
[src:aleut/scissor] While all scissors largely follow the same working principle, heavy-duty scissors intended for cutting tough materials tend to be called shears instead of scissors (e.g. pruning shears and grass shears), and some larger, two-handed implements are called *trimmers* instead (e.g. hedge trimmer).
[src:aleut/scissor] Choosing the optimal type of scissors/shears is crucial, as otherwise it can cause unwanted damage to the target material and/or the instrument itself.
[src:aleut/scissor] Surgical scissors, used to divide tissues and trim/reshape implants during surgical operations, have even a greater variety to deal with different anatomical and procedural circumstances.
[src:aleut/scissor] Most scissors have a ringed handle to allow readily opening for repeated cutting, and some even have spring between the shanks to assist opening (especially for shears with straight handle).
[src:aleut/scissor] While historically inexpensive, mass-produced scissors often have bare metal handles, modern scissors are often designed ergonomically with composite thermoplastic and rubber covering on handles, which are more comfortable for the hand.
[src:aleut/scissor] The noun *scissors* is treated as a plural noun and therefore takes a plural verb (e.g., *these scissors are*).
[src:aleut/scissor] Alternatively, the tool is referred to by the singular phrase *a pair of scissors*.
[src:aleut/scissor] The word *shears* is used to describe similar instruments that are larger in size and for heavier cutting.
[src:aleut/scissor] The Hangzhou Zhang Xiaoquan Company in Hangzhou, China, has been manufacturing scissors since 1663.
[src:aleut/scissor] Pivoted scissors were not manufactured in large numbers until 1761, when Robert Hinchliffe of Sheffield produced the first pair of modern-day scissors made of hardened and polished cast steel.
[src:aleut/scissor] His major challenge was to form the bows; first, he made them solid, then drilled a hole, and then filed away metal to make this large enough to admit the user's fingers.
[src:aleut/scissor] This process was laborious, and apparently Hinchliffe improved upon it in order to increase production.
[src:aleut/scissor] Hinchliffe lived in Cheney Square (now the site of Sheffield Town Hall), and set up a sign identifying himself as a "fine scissor manufacturer".
[src:aleut/scissor] He achieved strong sales in London and elsewhere.
[src:aleut/scissor] The vast majority of global scissor manufacturing takes place in China.
[src:aleut/scissor] As of 2019, China was responsible for 64.3% of worldwide scissors exports.
[src:aleut/scissor] When combined with Chinese Taipei exports, this rises to 68.3%.
[src:aleut/scissor] The Hangzhou Zhang Xiaoquan Company, founded in 1663, is one of the oldest continuously operating scissor manufacturers in the world.
[src:aleut/scissor] The company was nationalized in 1958 and now employs 1500 people who annually mass-produce an estimated seven million pairs of inexpensive scissors that retail for an average of US$4 each.
[src:aleut/scissor] In the late 14th century, the English word "scissors" came into usage.
[src:aleut/scissor] It was derived from the Old French word *cisoires*, which referred to shears.
[src:aleut/scissor] There are several historically important scissor-producing regions in France: Haute-Marne in Nogent-en Bassigny, Châtellereault, Thiers and Rouen.
[src:aleut/scissor] These towns, like many other scissor-producing communities, began with sabre, sword and bayonet production, which transitioned to scissors and other blades in the late 18th and early 19th centuries.
[src:aleut/scissor] Thiers, in the Puy-de-Dôme department of Auvergne, remains an important centre of scissor and cutlery production.
[src:aleut/scissor] It is home to both the Musée de la Coutellerie, which showcases the town's 800-year history of blade-making, as well as Coutellia, an industry tradeshow that advertises itself as one of the largest annual gatherings of artisanal blade-makers in the world.
[src:aleut/scissor] Germany was responsible for manufacturing just under 7% of global scissors exports in 2019.
[src:aleut/scissor] Often called "The City of Blades", Solingen, in North Rhine-Westphalia, has been a center for the manufacturing of scissors since medieval times.
[src:aleut/scissor] At the end of the 18th century it's estimated that there were over 300 scissorsmiths in Solingen.
[src:aleut/scissor] In 1995 the City of Solingen passed The Solingen Ordinance, an update to a 1930s law that decreed "Made in Solingen" stamps could only be applied to products almost entirely manufactured in the old industrial area of Solingen.
[src:aleut/scissor] In 2019 this applied to approximately 150 companies making high-quality blades of all kinds, including scissors.
[src:aleut/scissor] Friedrich Herder, founded in Solingen in 1727, is one of the oldest scissors manufacturers still operating in Germany.
[src:aleut/scissor] Premana, in Lecco Province, has its origins in ironworks and knife manufacturing beginning in the 16th century.
[src:aleut/scissor] In 1900 there were ten scissor manufacturing workshops, 20 in 1952 and 48 by 1960.
[src:aleut/scissor] Today, Consorzio Premax, an industrial partnership, organizes over 60 local companies involved in the manufacture of scissors for global markets.
[src:aleut/scissor] In 2019 Italy exported 3.5% of scissors manufactured globally.
[src:aleut/scissor] One of the oldest Premanese scissor manufacturing firms still in operation is Sanelli Ambrogio, which was founded in 1869.
[src:aleut/scissor] Scissormaking in Japan evolved from sword making in the 14th century.
[src:aleut/scissor] Seki, in Gifu Prefecture, was a renowned center of swordmaking beginning in the 1200s.
[src:aleut/scissor] After citizens were no longer permitted to carry swords, the city's blacksmiths turned to making scissors and knives.
[src:aleut/scissor] There are many specialized types of Japanese scissors, but sewing scissors were introduced by American Commodore Matthew Perry from the United States in 1854.
[src:aleut/scissor] The Sasuke workshop in Sakai City south of Osaka is run by Yasuhiro Hirakawa, a 5th generation scissorsmith.
[src:aleut/scissor] The company has been in operation since 1867.
[src:aleut/scissor] Yasuhiro Hirakawa is the last traditional scissormaker in Japan, making scissors in the traditional style where the blades are believed to be thinner, lighter and sharper than European scissors.
[src:aleut/scissor] In 2018 he was profiled in a documentary that featured a pair of his bonsai snips which retailed for US$35,000.
[src:aleut/scissor] In Solsona, Spain, scissor manufacturing began in the 16th century.
[src:aleut/scissor] At the industry's peak in the 18th century there were 24 workshops, organized as the Guild of Saint Eligius, the patron saint of knife makers.
[src:aleut/scissor] By the mid-1980s there were only two, and by 2021, Pallarès Solsona, founded in 1917 by Lluìs and Carles Pallarès Canal, and still family-operated, was the town's sole remaining artisanal scissor manufacturer.
[src:aleut/scissor] Sheffield was home to the first mass production of scissors beginning in 1761.
[src:aleut/scissor] By the 19th century there were an estimated 60 steel scissor companies in Sheffield.
[src:aleut/scissor] However, since the 1980s, industry globalization and a shift towards cheaper, mass-produced scissors created price deflation that many artisanal manufacturers could not compete with.
[src:aleut/scissor] The Sheffield scissor industry consisted of just two local companies in 2021.
[src:aleut/scissor] The two remaining Sheffield scissor manufacturers are William Whiteley, founded in 1760, and Ernest Wright, which was established in 1902.
[src:aleut/scissor] Both now focus on high-end/niche crafting of "products for life" rather than mass production.
[src:aleut/scissor] Between these two firms it is estimated that there are no more than ten "putter-togetherers" or "putters" who are the master-trained craftspeople responsible for high quality Sheffield scissor assembly.
[src:aleut/scissor] In 2020, Ernest Wright was recognized with the Award for Endangered Crafts by the British Heritage Crafts Association.
[src:aleut/scissor] There are two varieties of left-handed scissors.
[src:aleut/scissor] Many common left-handed scissors (often called "semi"-left-handed scissors) simply have reversed finger grips.
[src:aleut/scissor] The blades open and close as with right-handed scissors, so that users tend to pull the blades apart as they are cutting.
[src:aleut/scissor] This can be challenging for craftspeople as the blades still obscure the cut.
[src:aleut/scissor] "True" left-handed scissors have both reversed finger grips and reversed blade layout, like mirror images of right-handed scissors.
[src:aleut/scissor] A left-handed person accustomed to using semi-left handed scissors may find using true left-handed scissors difficult at first, as they may have learned to rely heavily on the strength of their thumb to pull the blades apart vs. pushing the blades together in order to cut.
[src:aleut/scissor] Some scissors are marketed as ambidextrous.
[src:aleut/scissor] These have symmetric handles so there is no distinction between the thumb and finger handles, and have very strong pivots so that the blades rotate without any lateral give.
[src:aleut/scissor] However, most "ambidextrous" scissors are in fact still right-handed in that the upper blade is on the right, and hence is on the outside when held in the right hand.
[src:aleut/scissor] Even if they cut successfully, the blade orientation will block the view of the cutting line for a left-handed person.
[src:aleut/scissor] True ambidextrous scissors are possible if the blades are double-edged and one handle is swung all the way around (to almost 360 degrees) so that what were the backs of the blades become the new cutting edges.
[src:aleut/scissor] U.S. patent 3,978,584 was awarded for true ambidextrous scissors.
[src:aleut/trouser] The oldest known trousers, dating to the period between the thirteenth and the tenth centuries BC, were found at the Yanghai cemetery in Turpan, Xinjiang (Tocharia), in present-day western China.
[src:aleut/trouser] Made of wool, the trousers had straight legs and wide crotches and were likely made for horseback riding.
[src:aleut/trouser] A pair of trouser-like leggings dating back to 3350 and 3105 BC were found in the Austria–Italy border worn by Ötzi.
[src:aleut/trouser] In most of Europe, trousers have been worn since ancient times and throughout the Medieval period, becoming the most common form of lower-body clothing for adult males in the modern world.
[src:aleut/trouser] Breeches were worn instead of trousers in early modern Europe by some men in higher classes of society.
[src:aleut/trouser] Distinctive formal trousers are traditionally worn with formal and semi-formal day attire.
[src:aleut/trouser] Since the mid-twentieth century, trousers have increasingly been worn by women as well.
[src:aleut/trouser] Jeans, made of denim, are a form of trousers for casual wear widely worn all over the world by people of both genders.
[src:aleut/trouser] Shorts are often preferred in hot weather or for some sports and also often by children and adolescents.
[src:aleut/trouser] Trousers are worn on the hips or waist and are often held up by buttons, elastic, a belt, or suspenders (braces).
[src:aleut/trouser] Unless elastic, and especially for men, trousers usually provide a zippered or buttoned fly.
[src:aleut/trouser] Jeans usually feature side and rear pockets with pocket openings placed slightly below the waist band.
[src:aleut/trouser] It is also possible for trousers to provide cargo pockets further down the legs.
[src:aleut/trouser] Maintenance of fit is more challenging for trousers than for some other garments.
[src:aleut/trouser] Leg-length can be adjusted with a hem, which helps to retain fit during the adolescent and early adulthood growth years.
[src:aleut/trouser] Tailoring adjustment of girth to accommodate weight gain or weight loss is relatively limited, and otherwise serviceable trousers might need to be replaced after a significant change in body composition.
[src:aleut/trouser] Higher-quality trousers often have extra fabric included in the centre-back seam allowance, so the waist can be let out further.
[src:aleut/trouser] In Scotland, a type of tartan trousers traditionally worn by Highlanders as an alternative to the Great Plaid and its predecessors is called *trews* or in the original Gaelic *triubhas*.
[src:aleut/trouser] This is the source of the English word *trousers*.
[src:aleut/trouser] Trews are still sometimes worn instead of the kilt at ceilidhs, weddings etc.
[src:aleut/trouser] Trousers are also known as *breeks* in Scots, the cognate of *breeches*.
[src:aleut/trouser] The item of clothing worn under trousers is called *pants*.
[src:aleut/trouser] The standard English form *trousers* is also used, but it is sometimes pronounced in a manner approximately represented by [ˈtruːzɨrz], as Scots did not completely undergo the Great Vowel Shift, and thus retains the vowel sound of the Gaelic *triubhas*, from which the word originates.
[src:aleut/trouser] In North America, Australia, and South Africa, *pants* is the general category term, whereas *trousers* (sometimes *slacks* in Australia and North America) often refers more specifically to tailored garments with a waistband, belt-loops, and a fly-front.
[src:aleut/trouser] In these dialects, elastic-waist knitted garments would be called *pants*, but not *trousers* (or *slacks*).
[src:aleut/trouser] North Americans call undergarments *underwear*, *underpants*, *undies*, or *panties* (the last are women's garments specifically) to differentiate them from other pants that are worn on the outside.
[src:aleut/trouser] The term *drawers* normally refers to undergarments, but in some dialects, may be found as a synonym for *breeches*, that is, trousers.
[src:aleut/trouser] In these dialects, the term *underdrawers* is used for undergarments.
[src:aleut/trouser] Many North Americans refer to their underpants by their type, such as *boxers* or *briefs*.
[src:aleut/trouser] In Australia, men's underwear also has various informal terms including *under-dacks*, *undies*, *dacks* or *jocks*.
[src:aleut/trouser] In New Zealand, men's underwear is known informally as *undies* or *dacks*.
[src:aleut/trouser] In India, underwear is also referred to as *innerwear*.
[src:aleut/trouser] The words *trouser* (or *pant*) instead of *trousers* (or *pants*) is sometimes used in the tailoring and fashion industries as a generic term, for instance when discussing styles, such as "a flared trouser", rather than as a specific item.
[src:aleut/trouser] The words *trousers* and *pants* are *pluralia tantum*, nouns that generally only appear in plural form—much like the words *scissors* and *tongs*, and as such *pair of trousers* is the usual correct form.
[src:aleut/trouser] However, the singular form is used in some compound words, such as *trouser-leg*, *trouser-press* and *trouser-bottoms*.
[src:aleut/trouser] Jeans are trousers typically made from denim or dungaree cloth.
[src:aleut/trouser] There are several different main types of pants and trousers, such as dress pants, jeans, khakis, chinos, leggings, overalls, and sweatpants.
[src:aleut/trouser] They can also be classified by fit, fabric, and other features.
[src:aleut/trouser] There is apparently no universal, overarching classification.
[src:aleut/trouser] There is some evidence, from figurative art, of trousers being worn in the Upper Paleolithic, as seen on the figurines found at the Siberian sites of Mal'ta and Buret'.
[src:aleut/trouser] Fabrics and technology for their construction are fragile and disintegrate easily, so often are not among artefacts discovered in archaeological sites.
[src:aleut/trouser] Trousers enter recorded history in the sixth century BC, on the rock carvings and artworks of Persepolis, and with the appearance of horse-riding Eurasian nomads in Greek ethnography.
[src:aleut/trouser] At this time, Iranian peoples such as Scythians, Sarmatians, Sogdians and Bactrians among others, along with Armenians and Eastern and Central Asian peoples such as the Xiongnu/Hunnu, are known to have worn trousers.
[src:aleut/trouser] Trousers are believed to have been worn by people of any gender among these early users.
[src:aleut/trouser] The ancient Greeks used the term ἀναξυρίδες (*anaxyrides*) for the trousers worn by Eastern nations and σαράβαρα (*sarabara*) for the loose trousers worn by the Scythians.
[src:aleut/trouser] However, they did not wear trousers since they thought them ridiculous, using the word θύλακοι (*thulakoi*), pl. of θύλακος (*thulakos*) 'sack', as a slang term for the loose trousers of Persians and other Middle Easterners.
[src:aleut/trouser] Republican Rome viewed the draped clothing of Greek and Minoan (Cretan) culture as an emblem of civilization and disdained trousers as the mark of barbarians.
[src:aleut/trouser] As the Roman Empire expanded beyond the Mediterranean basin, however, the greater warmth provided by trousers led to their adoption.
[src:aleut/trouser] Two types of trousers eventually saw widespread use in Rome: the *feminalia*, which fit snugly and usually fell to knee length or mid-calf length, and the *braccae*, loose-fitting trousers that were closed at the ankles.
[src:aleut/trouser] Both garments were adopted originally from the Celts of Europe, although later familiarity with the Persian Near East and the Germanic peoples increased acceptance.
[src:aleut/trouser] *Feminalia* and *braccae* both began use as military garments, spreading to civilian dress later, and were eventually made in a variety of materials, including leather, wool, cotton and silk.
[src:aleut/trouser] Trousers of various designs were worn throughout the Middle Ages in Europe, especially by men.
[src:aleut/trouser] Trousers in this period, generally called *braies*, varied in length and were often closed at the cuff or even had attached foot coverings, although open-legged pants were also seen.
[src:aleut/trouser] By the eighth century there is evidence of the wearing in Europe of two layers of trousers, especially among upper-class males.
[src:aleut/trouser] The under layer is today referred to by costume historians as *drawers*, although that usage did not emerge until the late sixteenth century.
[src:aleut/trouser] Over the drawers were worn trousers of wool or linen, which in the tenth century began to be referred to as *breeches* in many places.
[src:aleut/trouser] Tightness of fit and length of leg varied by period, class, and geography.
[src:aleut/trouser] As undergarments, these trousers became briefer or longer as the length of the various medieval outer garments changed, and were met by, and usually attached to, another garment variously called hose or stockings.
[src:aleut/trouser] In the fourteenth century it became common among the men of the noble and knightly classes to connect the hose directly to their pourpoints (the padded under jacket worn with armoured breastplates that would later evolve into the doublet) rather than to their drawers.
[src:aleut/trouser] In the fifteenth century, rising hemlines led to ever briefer drawers until they were dispensed with altogether by the most fashionable elites who joined their skin-tight hose back into trousers.
[src:aleut/trouser] These trousers, which we would today call tights but which were still called hose or sometimes joined hose at the time, emerged late in the fifteenth century and were conspicuous by their open crotch which was covered by an independently fastening front panel, the codpiece.
[src:aleut/trouser] The exposure of the hose to the waist was consistent with fifteenth-century trends, which also brought the pourpoint/doublet and the shirt, previously undergarments, into view, but the most revealing of these fashions were only ever adopted at court and not by the general population.
[src:aleut/trouser] Men's clothes in Hungary in the fifteenth century consisted of a shirt and trousers as underwear, and a dolman worn over them, as well as a short fur-lined or sheepskin coat.
[src:aleut/trouser] Hungarians generally wore simple trousers, only their colour being unusual; the dolman covered the greater part of the trousers.
[src:aleut/trouser] Around the turn of the sixteenth century it became conventional to separate hose into two pieces, one from the waist to the crotch which fastened around the top of the legs, called trunk hose, and the other running beneath it to the foot.
[src:aleut/trouser] The trunk hose soon reached down the thigh to fasten below the knee and were now usually called "breeches" to distinguish them from the lower-leg coverings still called *hose* or, sometimes *stockings*.
[src:aleut/trouser] By the end of the sixteenth century, the codpiece had also been incorporated into breeches which featured a *fly* or *fall front* opening.
[src:aleut/trouser] As a modernization measure, Tsar Peter the Great of Russia issued a decree in 1701 commanding every Russian man, other than clergy and peasant farmers, to wear trousers.
[src:aleut/trouser] During the French Revolution of 1789 and following, many male citizens of France adopted a working-class costume including ankle-length trousers, or pantaloons (named from a Commedia dell'Arte character named *Pantalone*) in place of the aristocratic knee-breeches (*culottes*).
[src:aleut/trouser] Pantaloons became fashionable in early nineteenth-century England and the Regency era.
[src:aleut/trouser] The style was introduced by Beau Brummell (1778–1840) and by mid-century had supplanted breeches as fashionable street-wear.
[src:aleut/trouser] At this point, even knee-length pants adopted the open bottoms of trousers (see shorts) and were worn by young boys, for sports, and in tropical climates.
[src:aleut/trouser] Breeches proper have survived into the twenty-first century as court dress, and also in baggy mid-calf (or three-quarter length) versions known as plus-fours or knickers worn for active sports and by young schoolboys.
[src:aleut/trouser] Types of breeches are also still worn today by fencers, baseball and American football players, and by equestrians.
[src:aleut/trouser] Sailors may have played a role in the worldwide dissemination of trousers as a fashion.
[src:aleut/trouser] In the seventeenth and eighteenth centuries, sailors wore baggy trousers known as *galligaskins*.
[src:aleut/trouser] Sailors also pioneered the wearing of jeans – trousers made of denim.
[src:aleut/trouser] These became more popular in the late nineteenth century in the American West because of their ruggedness and durability.
[src:aleut/trouser] Starting around the mid-nineteenth century, Wigan pit-brow women scandalized Victorian society by wearing trousers for their work at the local coal mines.
[src:aleut/trouser] They wore skirts over their trousers and rolled them up to their waists to keep them out of the way.
[src:aleut/trouser] Although pit-brow lasses worked above ground at the pit-head, their task of sorting and shovelling coal involved hard manual labour, so wearing the usual long skirts of the time would have greatly hindered their movements.
[src:aleut/trouser] The Korean word for trousers, *baji* (originally *pajibaji*) first appears in recorded history around the turn of the fifteenth century, but pants may have been in use by Korean society for some time.
[src:aleut/trouser] From at least this time pants were worn by both sexes in Korea.
[src:aleut/trouser] Men wore trousers either as outer garments or beneath skirts, while it was unusual for adult women to wear their pants (termed *sokgot*) without a covering skirt.
[src:aleut/trouser] As in Europe, a wide variety of styles came to define regions, time periods and age and gender groups, from the unlined *gouei* to the padded *sombaji*.
[src:aleut/trouser] In Western society, it was Eastern culture that inspired French designer Paul Poiret (1879–1944) to be one of the first to design pants for women.
[src:aleut/trouser] In 1913, Poiret created loose-fitting, wide-leg trousers for women called harem pants, which were based on the costumes of the popular ballet *Sheherazade*.
[src:aleut/trouser] Written by Nikolai Rimsky-Korsakov in 1888, Sheherazade was based on a collection of legends from the Middle East called 1001 Arabian Nights.
[src:aleut/trouser] In the early twentieth century, women air pilots and other working women often wore trousers.
[src:aleut/trouser] Frequent photographs from the 1930s of actresses Marlene Dietrich and Katharine Hepburn in trousers helped make trousers acceptable for women.
[src:aleut/trouser] During World War II, women employed in factories or doing other "men's work" on war service wore trousers when the job demanded it.
[src:aleut/trouser] In the post-war era, trousers became acceptable casual wear for gardening, the beach, and other leisure pursuits.
[src:aleut/trouser] In Britain during World War II the rationing of clothing prompted women to wear their husbands' civilian clothes, including trousers, to work while the men were serving in the armed forces.
[src:aleut/trouser] This was partly because they were seen as practical for work, but also so that women could keep their clothing allowance for other uses.
[src:aleut/trouser] As this practice of wearing trousers became more widespread and as the men's clothing wore out, replacements were needed.
[src:aleut/trouser] By the summer of 1944, it was reported that sales of women's trousers were five times more than the previous year.
[src:aleut/trouser] In 1919, Luisa Capetillo challenged mainstream society by becoming the first woman in Puerto Rico to wear trousers in public.
[src:aleut/trouser] Capetillo was sent to jail for what was considered to be a crime, but the charges were later dropped.
[src:aleut/trouser] In the 1960s, André Courrèges introduced long trousers for women as a fashion item, leading to the era of the pantsuit and designer jeans and the gradual erosion of social prohibitions against girls and women wearing trousers in schools, the workplace and in fine restaurants.
[src:aleut/trouser] Charlotte Reid (R-Ill.) became the first woman to wear trousers in the US Congress.
[src:aleut/trouser] Pat Nixon was the first American First Lady to wear trousers in public.
[src:aleut/trouser] In 1989, California state senator Rebecca Morgan became the first woman to wear trousers in a US state senate.
[src:aleut/trouser] Hillary Clinton was the first woman to wear trousers in an official American First Lady portrait.
[src:aleut/trouser] Women were not allowed to wear trousers on the US Senate floor until 1993.
[src:aleut/trouser] In Malawi women were not legally allowed to wear trousers under President Kamuzu Banda's rule until 1994.
[src:aleut/trouser] Since 2004 the International Skating Union has allowed women to wear trousers instead of skirts in ice-skating competitions.
[src:aleut/trouser] In 2009, journalist Lubna Hussein was fined the equivalent of $200 when a court found her guilty of violating Sudan's decency laws by wearing trousers.
[src:aleut/trouser] In 2012 the Royal Canadian Mounted Police began to allow women to wear trousers and boots with all their formal uniforms.
[src:aleut/trouser] In 2012 and 2013, some Mormon women participated in "Wear Pants to Church Day", in which they wore trousers to church instead of the customary dresses to encourage gender equality within the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints.
[src:aleut/trouser] More than one thousand women participated in 2012.
[src:aleut/trouser] In 2013, Turkey's parliament ended a ban on women lawmakers wearing trousers in its assembly.
[src:aleut/trouser] The bylaw was originally intended to prevent women from wearing the pantalons fashionable with Parisian rebels in the French Revolution.
[src:aleut/trouser] In 2014, an Indian family court in Mumbai ruled that a husband objecting to his wife wearing a kurta and jeans and forcing her to wear a sari amounts to cruelty inflicted by the husband and can be a ground to seek divorce.
[src:aleut/trouser] The wife was thus granted a divorce on the ground of cruelty as defined under section 27(1)(d) of the Special Marriage Act, 1954.
[src:aleut/trouser] Until 2016 some female crew members on British Airways were required to wear British Airways' standard "ambassador" uniform, which has not traditionally included trousers.
[src:aleut/trouser] In 2017, The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints announced that its female employees could wear "professional pantsuits and dress slacks" while at work; dresses and skirts had previously been required.
[src:aleut/trouser] In 2018 it was announced that female missionaries of that church could wear dress slacks except when attending the temple and during Sunday worship services, baptismal services, and mission leadership and zone conferences.
[src:aleut/trouser] In 2019, Virgin Atlantic began to allow its female flight attendants to wear trousers.
[src:aleut/trouser] Pleats located just below the waistband on the front typify many styles of formal and casual trousers, including suit trousers and khakis.
[src:aleut/trouser] There may be one, two, three, or no pleats, which may face either direction.
[src:aleut/trouser] When the pleats open toward the pockets they are called reverse pleats (typical of most trousers today) and when they open toward the fly they are known as forward pleats.
[src:aleut/trouser] In modern trousers, men's models generally have pockets for carrying small items such as wallets, keys or mobile phones, but women's trousers often do not – and sometimes have what are called Potemkin pockets, a fake slit sewn shut.
[src:aleut/trouser] If there are pockets, they are often much smaller than in men's clothes.
[src:aleut/trouser] In 2018, journalists at The Pudding found less than half of women's front pockets could fit a thin wallet, let alone a handheld phone and keys.
[src:aleut/trouser] Trouser-makers can finish the legs by hemming the bottom to prevent fraying.
[src:aleut/trouser] Trousers with turn-ups (cuffs in American English), after hemming, are rolled outward and sometimes pressed or stitched into place.
[src:aleut/trouser] A fly is a covering over an opening join concealing the mechanism, such as a zipper, velcro, or buttons, used to join the opening.
[src:aleut/trouser] In trousers, this is most commonly an opening covering the groin, which makes the pants easier to put on or take off.
[src:aleut/trouser] The opening also allows men to urinate without lowering their trousers.
[src:aleut/trouser] Trousers have varied historically in whether or not they have a fly.
[src:aleut/trouser] Originally, hose did not cover the area between the legs.
[src:aleut/trouser] This was instead covered by a doublet or by a codpiece.
[src:aleut/trouser] When breeches were worn, during the Regency period for example, they were fall-fronted (or broad fall).
[src:aleut/trouser] Later, after trousers (pantaloons) were invented, the fly-front (split fall) emerged.
[src:aleut/trouser] The panelled front returned as a sporting option, such as in riding breeches, but is now hardly ever used, a fly being by far the most common fastening.
[src:aleut/trouser] Most flies now use a zipper, though button-fly pants continue to be available.
[src:aleut/trouser] At present, most trousers are held up through the assistance of a belt which is passed through the **belt loops** on the waistband of the trousers.
[src:aleut/trouser] However, this was traditionally a style acceptable only for casual trousers and work trousers; suit trousers and formal trousers were suspended by the use of braces (*suspenders* in American English) attached to buttons located on the interior or exterior of the waistband.
[src:aleut/trouser] Today, this remains the preferred method of trouser support amongst adherents of classical British tailoring.
[src:aleut/trouser] Many men claim this method is more effective and more comfortable because it requires no cinching of the waist or periodic adjustment.
[src:aleut/trouser] In modern Western society, males customarily wear trousers and not skirts or dresses.
[src:aleut/trouser] There are exceptions, however, such as the ceremonial Scottish kilt and Greek fustanella, as well as robes or robe-like clothing such as the cassocks of clergy and the academic robes, both rarely worn today in daily use.
[src:aleut/trouser] Among certain groups, low-rise, baggy trousers exposing underwear became fashionable; for example, among skaters and in 1990s hip hop fashion.
[src:aleut/trouser] This fashion is called sagging or, alternatively, "busting slack".
[src:aleut/trouser] These groups permit women to wear underpants as long as they are hidden.
[src:aleut/trouser] By contrast, many Muslim sects approve of pants as they are considered more modest than any skirt that is shorter than ankle length.
[src:aleut/trouser] However, some mosques require ankle length trousers for both Muslims and non-Muslims on the premises.
[src:aleut/trouser] The Catholic Pope Nicholas I approved of both men and women wearing pants.
[src:aleut/trouser] The wife was thus granted a divorce on the ground of cruelty as defined under section 27(1)(d) of Special Marriage Act, 1954.
[src:aleut/trouser] In Rome in 1992, a 45-year-old driving instructor was accused of rape.
[src:aleut/trouser] When he picked up an 18-year-old for her first driving lesson, he allegedly raped her for an hour, then told her that if she was to tell anyone he would kill her.
[src:aleut/trouser] Later that night she told her parents and her parents agreed to help her press charges.
[src:aleut/trouser] While the alleged rapist was convicted and sentenced, the Supreme Court of Cassation overturned the conviction in 1998 because the victim wore tight jeans.
[src:aleut/trouser] It was argued that she must have necessarily have had to help her attacker remove her jeans, thus making the act consensual ("because the victim wore very, very tight jeans, she had to help him remove them...and by removing the jeans...it was no longer rape but consensual sex").
[src:aleut/trouser] The court stated in its decision "it is a fact of common experience that it is nearly impossible to slip off tight jeans even partly without the active collaboration of the person who is wearing them." This ruling sparked widespread feminist protest.
[src:aleut/trouser] The day after the decision, women in the Italian Parliament protested by wearing jeans and holding placards that read "Jeans: An Alibi for Rape".
[src:aleut/trouser] As a sign of support, the California Senate and Assembly followed suit.
[src:aleut/trouser] Soon Patricia Giggans, executive director of the Los Angeles Commission on Assaults Against Women, (now Peace Over Violence) made Denim Day an annual event.
[src:aleut/trouser] As of 2011 at least 20 U.S. states officially recognize Denim Day in April.
[src:aleut/trouser] Wearing jeans on this day, 22 April, has become an international symbol of protest.
[src:aleut/trouser] In 2008 the Supreme Court of Cassation overturned the ruling, so there is no longer a "denim" defense to the charge of rape.
[src:aleut/trouser] In Malawi, women were not legally allowed to wear trousers under President Kamuzu Banda's rule until 1994.
[src:aleut/trouser] Capetillo was sent to jail for what was then considered to be a crime, but the judge later dropped the charges against her.
[src:aleut/trouser] In Sudan, Article 152 of the Memorandum to the 1991 Penal Code prohibits the wearing of "obscene outfits" in public.
[src:aleut/trouser] This law has been used to arrest and prosecute women wearing trousers.
[src:aleut/trouser] Thirteen women including journalist Lubna al-Hussein were arrested in Khartoum in July 2009 for wearing trousers; ten of the women pleaded guilty and were flogged with ten lashes and fined 250 Sudanese pounds apiece.
[src:aleut/trouser] Lubna al-Hussein considers herself a good Muslim and asserts "Islam does not say whether a woman can wear trousers or not.
[src:aleut/trouser] But it is insulting." She was eventually found guilty and fined the equivalent of $200 rather than being flogged.
[src:aleut/trouser] In May 2004, in Louisiana, Democrat and state legislator Derrick Shepherd proposed a bill that would make it a crime to appear in public wearing trousers below the waist and thereby exposing one's skin or "intimate clothing".
[src:aleut/trouser] In February 2005, Virginia legislators tried to pass a similar law that would have made punishable by a $50 fine "any person who, while in a public place, intentionally wears and displays his below-waist undergarments, intended to cover a person's intimate parts, in a lewd or indecent manner".
[src:aleut/trouser] (It is not clear whether, with the same coverage by the trousers, exposing underwear was considered worse than exposing bare skin, or whether the latter was already covered by another law.) The law passed in the Virginia House of Delegates.
[src:aleut/trouser] However, various criticisms to it arose.
[src:aleut/trouser] For example, newspaper columnists and radio talk show hosts consistently said that since most people that would be penalized under the law would be young African-American men, the law would thus be a form of racial discrimination.
[src:aleut/trouser] Virginia's state senators voted against passing the law.
[src:aleut/trouser] In California, Government Code Section 12947.5 (part of the California Fair Employment and Housing Act (FEHA)) expressly protects the right to wear pants.
[src:aleut/trouser] Thus, the standard California FEHA discrimination complaint form includes an option for "denied the right to wear pants".
